<paragraph blockId="6.[831,1437,305,584]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">
A widely distributed genus comprising 284 species (
<bibRefCitation author="Nuss M. &amp; Landry B. &amp; Vegliante F. &amp; Trankner A. &amp; Mally R. &amp; Hayden J. E. &amp; Bauer F. &amp; Segerer A. &amp; Li H. &amp; Schouten R. &amp; Solis M. A. &amp; Trofimova T. &amp; De Prins J. &amp; Speidel W." box="[839,1052,337,361]" journalOrPublisher="www. pyraloidea. org" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" refId="ref13003" refString="Nuss M., Landry B., Vegliante F., Trankner A., Mally R., Hayden J. E., Bauer F., Segerer A., Li H., Schouten R., Solis M. A., Trofimova T., De Prins J., Speidel W. 2014. Global Information System on Pyraloidea. www. pyraloidea. org." title="Global Information System on Pyraloidea" type="book" year="2014">
Nuss 
<emphasis box="[909,979,337,361]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">et al.,</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
). The larvae web and often roll leaves, shoots, and flowers head of a variety of herbaceous plants, but most of the species were reared from 
<taxonomicName authority="(Munroe, 1976)" authorityName="Munroe" authorityYear="1976" baseAuthorityName="Munroe" baseAuthorityYear="1976" box="[895,1200,433,456]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">
Lamiaceae (
<bibRefCitation author="Munroe E. G." box="[1030,1192,433,456]" editor="Dominick R. B." journalOrPublisher="E. W. Classey Ltd. and The Wedge Entomological Research Foundation, London" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" refId="ref12766" refString="Munroe E. G. 1976. Pyraloidea Pyralidae comprising the subfamily Pyraustinae tribe Pyraustini (part 1) [pp. 1 - 78, pls 1 - 4, A-H; (conclusion); pp. 79 - 150, pls 5 - 9, J-U, pp. xiiixvii]. In: Dominick R. B. et al., The Moths of America north of Mexico 13.2 A &amp; 13.2 B. E. W. Classey Ltd. and The Wedge Entomological Research Foundation, London." title="Pyraloidea Pyralidae comprising the subfamily Pyraustinae tribe Pyraustini (part 1)" type="book" volumeTitle="The Moths of America north of Mexico 13.2 A &amp; 13.2 B" year="1976">Munroe, 1976</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Three species occur in the 
<collectingRegion box="[909,1026,465,488]" country="Ecuador" name="Galapagos" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Galápagos</collectingRegion>
. The moths are generally small and slender and the valva of the male genitalia usually bears a single basally directed or recurved setose or scaled clasper (
<bibRefCitation author="Munroe E. G." box="[921,1078,561,584]" editor="Dominick R. B." journalOrPublisher="E. W. Classey Ltd. and The Wedge Entomological Research Foundation, London" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" refId="ref12766" refString="Munroe E. G. 1976. Pyraloidea Pyralidae comprising the subfamily Pyraustinae tribe Pyraustini (part 1) [pp. 1 - 78, pls 1 - 4, A-H; (conclusion); pp. 79 - 150, pls 5 - 9, J-U, pp. xiiixvii]. In: Dominick R. B. et al., The Moths of America north of Mexico 13.2 A &amp; 13.2 B. E. W. Classey Ltd. and The Wedge Entomological Research Foundation, London." title="Pyraloidea Pyralidae comprising the subfamily Pyraustinae tribe Pyraustini (part 1)" type="book" volumeTitle="The Moths of America north of Mexico 13.2 A &amp; 13.2 B" year="1976">Munroe, 1976</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
